# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:railway-platform/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:railway-platform/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:railway-platform/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:railway-platform/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:railway-platform/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:railway-platform/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:railway-platform/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:railway-platform/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:railway-platform/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:railway-platform/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:railway-platform/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:railway-platform/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:railway-platform/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:railway-platform/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:railway-platform/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:railway-platform/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:railway-platform/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:railway-platform/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:railway-platform/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:railway-platform/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:railway-platform/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:railway-platform/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:railway-platform/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:railway-platform/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:railway-platform/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:railway-platform/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:railway-platform/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:railway-platform/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:railway-platform/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:railway-platform/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:railway-platform/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:railway-platform/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:railway-platform/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:railway-platform/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] An **environment variable** is a user-definable value that can affect the way running processes will behave on a computer.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Environment variables are part of the environment in which a process runs.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] For example, a running process can query the value of the TEMP environment variable to discover a suitable location to store temporary files, or the HOME or USERPROFILE variable to find the directory structure owned by the user running the process.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] They were introduced in their modern form in 1979 with Version 7 Unix, so are included in all Unix operating system flavors and variants from that point onward including Linux and macOS.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] From PC DOS 2.0 in 1982, all succeeding Microsoft operating systems, including Microsoft Windows, and OS/2 also have included them as a feature, although with somewhat different syntax, usage and standard variable names.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In all Unix and Unix-like systems, as well as on Windows, each process has its own separate set of environment variables.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] By default, when a process is created, it inherits a duplicate run-time environment of its parent process, except for explicit changes made by the parent when it creates the child.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] At the API level, these changes must be done between running `fork` and `exec`.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Alternatively, from command shells such as bash, a user can change environment variables for a particular command invocation by indirectly invoking it via `env` or using the `ENVIRONMENT_VARIABLE=VALUE <command>` notation.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] A running program can access the values of environment variables for configuration purposes.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Shell scripts and batch files use environment variables to communicate data and preferences to child processes.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] They can also be used to store temporary values for reference later in a shell script.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] However, in Unix, non-exported variables are preferred for this as they do not leak outside the process.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In Unix, an environment variable that is changed in a script or compiled program will only affect that process and possibly child processes.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The parent process and any unrelated processes will not be affected.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Similarly, changing or removing a variable's value inside a DOS or Windows batch file will change the variable for the duration of `COMMAND.COM`or `CMD.EXE`'s existence, respectively.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In Unix, the environment variables are normally initialized during system startup by the system init startup scripts, and hence inherited by all other processes in the system.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Users can, and often do, augment them in the profile script for the command shell they are using.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In Microsoft Windows, each environment variable's default value is stored in the Windows Registry or set in the `AUTOEXEC.BAT` file.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] On Unix, a setuid program is given an environment chosen by its caller, but it runs with different authority from its caller.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The dynamic linker will usually load code from locations specified by the environment variables `$LD_LIBRARY_PATH` and `$LD_PRELOAD` and run it with the process's authority.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] If a setuid program did this, it would be insecure, because its caller could get it to run arbitrary code and hence misuse its authority.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] For this reason, libc unsets these environment variables at startup in a setuid process. setuid programs usually unset unknown environment variables and check others or set them to reasonable values.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In general, the collection of environment variables function as an associative array where both the keys and values are strings.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The interpretation of characters in either string differs among systems.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] When data structures such as lists need to be represented, it is common to use a colon (common on Unix and Unix-like) or semicolon-delineated (common on Windows and DOS) list.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The variables can be used both in scripts and on the command line.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] They are usually referenced by putting special symbols in front of or around the variable name.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] By convention, names of environment variables are normally expressed in all capital letters.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] This helps keep environment variables distinctly different from other variables and identifiers used in programming codes.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Nevertheless, note that case sensitivity in environment variable names differs between operating systems.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] That is, Unix-like operating systems are case-sensitive with respect to environment variable names, while DOS, OS/2, and Windows are not case-sensitive.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In most Unix and Unix-like command-line shells, an environment variable's value is retrieved by placing a `$` sign before the variable's name.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] If necessary, the name can also be surrounded by braces.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the names of environment variables are case-sensitive.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The command **`env`** displays all environment variables and their values.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The command **`printenv`** can also be used to print a single variable by giving that variable name as the sole argument to the command.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows command-line interpreters such as `COMMAND.COM` and `CMD.EXE`, an environment variable is retrieved by placing a `%` sign before and after it.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows command-line interpreters as well as their API, upper or lower case is not distinguished for environment variable names.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The environment variable named `HOMEDRIVE` contains the drive letter (plus its trailing `:` colon) of the user's home directory, whilst `HOMEPATH` contains the full path of the user's home directory within that drive.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The command **`SET`** (with no arguments) displays all environment variables and their values.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In Windows NT and later `set` can also be used to print all variables whose name begins with a given prefix by giving the prefix as the sole argument to the command.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In PowerShell, upper or lower case is not distinguished for environment variable names.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The commands `env` and `set` can be used to set environment variables and are often incorporated directly into the shell.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The following commands can also be used, but are often dependent on a certain shell.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] A few simple principles govern how environment variables achieve their effect.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Environment variables are local to the process in which they were set.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] If two shell processes are spawned and the value of an environment variable is changed in one, that change will not be seen by the other.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] When a child process is created, it inherits all the environment variables and their values from the parent process.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Usually, when a program calls another program, it first creates a child process by forking, then the child adjusts the environment as needed and lastly the child replaces itself with the program to be called.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] This procedure gives the calling program control over the environment of the called program.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In Unix shells, variables may be assigned without the **`export`** keyword.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Variables defined in this way are displayed by the **`set`** command, but are *not* true environment variables, as they are stored only by the shell and are unknown to all other processes.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The `printenv` command will not display them, and child processes do not inherit them.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The persistence of an environment variable can be session-wide or system-wide.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] The **`SET`** command without any arguments displays all environment variables along with their values; **`SET " "`**, zero or more spaces, will include internal variables too.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In `CMD.EXE`, it is possible to assign local variables that will not be global using the **`SETLOCAL`** command and **`ENDLOCAL`** to restore the environment.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In PHP the `putenv()` function should be used.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Contains a colon-separated list of directories that the shell searches for commands that do not contain a slash in their name (commands with slashes are interpreted as file names to execute, and the shell attempts to execute the files directly).
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] is often used for convenience in various shell scripts (and other contexts).
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Using the environment variable also gives the user the possibility to point to another directory.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] This variable points to the current directory.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Equivalent to the output of the command pwd when called without arguments.
