[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Under DOS, the *master environment* is provided by the primary command processor, which inherits the *pre-environment* defined in `CONFIG.SYS` when first loaded.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Its size can be configured through the `COMMAND /E:n` parameter between 160 and 32767 bytes.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] *Local environment* segments inherited to child processes are typically reduced down to the size of the contents they hold.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Some command-line processors (like 4DOS) allow to define a minimum amount of free environment space that will be available when launching secondary shells.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In principle, MS-DOS 7.0 and higher also supports lowercase variable names (`%windir%`), but provides no means for the user to define them.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Environment variable names containing lowercase letters are stored in the environment just like normal environment variables, but remain invisible to most DOS software, since they are written to expect uppercase variables only.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Some command processors limit the maximum length of a variable name to 80 characters.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] While principally only limited by the size of the *environment segment*, some DOS and 16-bit Windows programs do not expect the contents of environment variables to exceed 128 characters.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] DR-DOS `COMMAND.COM` supports environment variables up to 255, 4DOS even up to 512 characters.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] Since `COMMAND.COM` can be configured (via `/L:128..1024`) to support command lines up to 1024 characters internally under MS-DOS 7.0 and higher, environment variables should be expected to contain at least 1024 characters as well.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In some versions of DR-DOS, the environment passed to drivers, which often do not need their environment after installation, can be shrunken or relocated through `SETENV` or `INSTALL[HIGH]`/`LOADHIGH` options `/Z` (zero environment), `/D[:loaddrive]` (substitute drive, e.g.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] `B:TSR.COM`) and `/E` (relocate environment above program) in order to minimize the driver's effectively resulting resident memory footprint.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] In batch mode, non-existent environment variables are replaced by a zero-length string.
[src:railway-platform/environment-variable-p01] This variable contains a semicolon-delimited list of directories in which to search for files.
